document:
Lucy is the first space mission to explore a diverse population of small bodies known as the Jupiter Trojan asteroids. These remnants of our early solar system are trapped on stable orbits associated with - but not close to - the giant planet Jupiter. Trojan asteroids orbit in two "swarms" that lead and follow Jupiter in its orbit around the Sun and are thought to be comparable in number to the objects in the main asteroid belt between the orbits of Mars and Jupiter.

Over its 12-year mission, Lucy will explore a record-breaking number of asteroids: it will fly by two (plus a newly discovered satellite) in the belt of asteroids that circle the Sun between the orbits of Mars and Jupiter, and then eight Trojans, which includes five asteroid targets and the satellites of three of those. Lucy also will fly by Earth three times to get a push from its gravity, making it the first spacecraft to return to the vicinity of Earth from the outer solar system.

expand_doc:
NASA's Lucy Spacecraft Set to Launch in October 2021 to Explore Jupiter's Trojan Asteroids

NASA is gearing up for an exciting mission with the upcoming launch of Lucy, a spacecraft designed to study the Trojan asteroids, remnants from the early solar system. Scheduled for liftoff in October 2021, Lucy will embark on a journey of over 500 million miles to investigate these asteroids located in Jupiter's orbit.

Named after the famous fossilized hominid, Lucy will utilize Earth's gravity to propel itself towards the Greek and Trojan camps, two distinct groups of asteroids. Among the targets for Lucy's exploration are the asteroids Donaldjohanson and Kowal, located in the asteroid belt.

Over the course of the expected 12-year mission, Lucy will conduct in-depth studies of the geology, surface composition, and history of the Trojan asteroids. This mission marks a significant step in unraveling the mysteries of our solar system's early days and promises groundbreaking discoveries in the field of planetary science.

Arnold Schwarzenegger

Governor of California from 2003 to 2011

Significant Facts

Born: July 30, 1947 in Thal, Austria

Married: Maria Shriver on April 26, 1986 (The couple filed for divorce in 2011.)

Political Party: Republican

Arnold Schwarzenegger was born in Thal, Austria, a small village bordering the Styrian capital of Graz. He immigrated to the United States in 1968 and became a U.S. citizen in 1983.

Schwarzenegger earned a BA in Business and International Economics at the University of Wisconsin-Superior. He received an honorary Doctorate from the University of Wisconsin-Superior in 1996 and an honorary Doctorate from Chapman University in 2002.
    
An increasingly politically active Republican during the 1990s, Schwarzenegger ran for the California governorship and won when Gray Davis was recalled in 2003. Schwarzenegger was sworn in as the 38th Governor of California on November 17, 2003, following careers in body building, business and entertainment. Schwarzenegger was the first foreign-born governor of California since Irish-born Governor John G. Downey (Governor of California from 1860 to 1862). While governor, Schwarzenegger focused on reducing California's greenhouse gas emissions, increasing the minimum wage, and updating the workers' compensation system. He was also a proponent of physical education and after-school programs, and supported the After-School Education & Safety Act, which passed in 2002.

expand_doc:
Arnold Schwarzenegger: From Bodybuilder to Governor

Arnold Schwarzenegger, born in Austria, has had a remarkable journey from professional bodybuilder to successful actor and politician. Serving as the 38th Governor of California from 2003 to 2011, Schwarzenegger made a name for himself not only in politics but also in Hollywood.

Before his acting career took off, Schwarzenegger was a prominent figure in the bodybuilding world, winning the prestigious Mr. Olympia contest seven times. His transition to acting was smooth, landing roles in blockbuster films like "Predator" in 1987 and his first major role in "Conan the Barbarian."

Aside from his entertainment career, Schwarzenegger is also known for his marriage to Maria Shriver, a member of the Kennedy family, and their four children. In 1983, he became a naturalized U.S. citizen, further solidifying his ties to the country.

Fans of Schwarzenegger will remember his iconic catchphrase "I'll be back" from the Terminator movies, solidifying his status as a cultural icon. Beyond his entertainment career, Schwarzenegger has been actively involved in philanthropic efforts and charity work, using his platform to make a positive impact on society.

Arnold Schwarzenegger's journey from bodybuilder to Governor exemplifies his diverse talents and unwavering commitment to success in all his endeavors.
